Almouse 24-Jun-19 03:06 AM
architectural question: any opinions on the best way to build a supervisor/manager for non-trivial objects? i've had to do it a few times, and the code always ends out coming up cludgy, presumably partially because lua's class thing isn't so trong
to pick a relevant example, let's suppose i want to create a system that allows creation of lua-operated trigger regions (i.e. they don't correspond to hammer regions)
one thing i could do is to create a class just for trigger regions, and have each trigger region operate fully independently, which is fine enough at times
but i might want to have a supervisor that instead holds a reference to all trigger regions, and then performs updates/changes to them
Alacrity 24-Jun-19 03:09 AM

director has global control manager has an AoE and associated spawn_point vectors
each level is able to deactivate the bottom
Almouse 24-Jun-19 03:10 AM
sure, i've done something like that for smaller structures, but i found that once self references start creeping in, things can get gross
trying to think of an example at the right level of complexity
let's suppose for example that i have a class Level, with instances Level1, Level2, etc., that are responsible for setting up the map for each level.
